THE THREE LIFECYCLE PHASES: THINK, TRANSFORM, THRIVE
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

For each lifecycle phase, IBM Garage uses practices from: Enterprise Design
Thinking, Lean Startup, Agile, DevOps, Site Reliability Engineering (SRE),
and organizational change management.

PHASE 1: THINK (Co-Create / Discover)
Purpose: Go from a business challenge to a validated idea.
Duration: Typically 2-4 weeks.

A combined team of diverse subject matter experts (SMEs) is immersed in
intensive design thinking and research to expose the true nature of the
client's opportunity. Activities include:
- Stakeholder interviews and contextual user research
- Enterprise Design Thinking workshops (Hills, Playbacks, Sponsor Users)
- Pain point identification and opportunity mapping
- Hypothesis formation: "We believe that [solution] will result in [outcome]
  for [user], measured by [metric]"
- Definition of a Minimum Viable Product (MVP)
- Initial risk and dependency identification

Key deliverables: Defined Hills, validated MVP scope, Go/No-Go decision.

PHASE 2: TRANSFORM (Co-Execute / Build)
Purpose: Build, test, and validate the MVP with Agile and DevOps practices.
Duration: Typically 4-12 weeks per MVP cycle.

A solution development cycle using Agile and DevOps to quickly launch and test
an MVP, capitalizing on IBM's hybrid cloud and AI expertise. IBM uses Build
practices from Extreme Programming, DevOps, and lean design:
- Automated continuous integration (CI)
- Refactoring and pair programming
- Iterative software design
- Reference architectures
- Aligning development and ops for success
- Validating designs with Sponsor Users
- Automating application monitoring

IBM pilots MVPs to prove hypotheses using business analytics. The core
question: "What aspects of this idea need testing to determine whether
continued investment is warranted?" This is the fail fast, learn fast principle.

For a single MVP: one squad, one MVP, dual objectives:
1. Developing the MVP
2. Trying out the Garage Method as a new way of working

PHASE 3: THRIVE (Co-Operate / Scale)
Purpose: Harden and scale the solution and the new culture of innovation.

Activities:
- Hardening the MVP for production readiness
- Scaling from squad to enterprise-wide adoption
- Site Reliability Engineering (SRE) practices
- Establishing sustainable DevSecOps pipelines
- Organizational change: shifting from silos to squads, waterfall to agile
- Embedding new ways of working as permanent culture

